<h2 id="add-a-person-to-the-website">Add a person to the website</h2>
<p>You need:</p>
<ul>
  <li>The person‚Äôs name</li>
  <li>The person‚Äôs personal website (optional)</li>
  <li>The person‚Äôs photo</li>
  <li>The person‚Äôs bio</li>
</ul>

<ol>
  <li>Add the person‚Äôs photo into the images/members folder and name it ‚ÄòNAME.jpg‚Äô</li>
  <li>Add the person‚Äôs information to _data/alpslab.yml following the formatting shown there. Be sure to follow the formatting precisely, as missing spaces/incorrect line breaks may break the website. Add the person in the correct section (Graduate students, Masters Students, etc.)</li>
  <li>Follow instructions under ‚Äúpublish changes‚Äù</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="change-lab-member-to-lab-alumni">Change Lab member to Lab Alumni</h2>
<ol>
  <li>Navigate to _data/alpslab.yml</li>
  <li>Find their data entry, copy it, then delete it</li>
  <li>Re-add their data entry to the ‚ÄúLab Alumni‚Äù section, including only their name, webpage (if they have one), and image.</li>
  <li>Follow instructions under ‚Äúpublish changes‚Äù</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="change-the-heading-picture">Change the heading picture</h2>
<p>You need:</p>
<ul>
  <li>the new lab image</li>
</ul>

<ol>
  <li>Go to images/ and rename the current ‚Äòlab_members.jpg‚Äô to ‚Äòlab_members[year photo was taken].jpg‚Äô.</li>
  <li>Add your new image in this folder and name it ‚Äòlab_members.jpg‚Äô</li>
  <li>Follow instructions under ‚Äúpublish changes‚Äù</li>
</ol>

<h1 id="publications">Publications</h1>

<h2 id="naming-nomenclature">Naming Nomenclature</h2>

<p>Bibtex entry keys and pdf names should be identical in order to link the [preprint] button with the pdf. The bib.bib file is ordered chronolocially with ‚Äúsubmitted‚Äù and ‚Äúto appear‚Äù articles at the bottom.</p>

<p>The bib entry key and pdf name nomenclature used is: [year][AuthorLastName]</p>
<ul>
  <li>use CamelCase</li>
  <li>Use the last names of the first two authors, if there are more than two append the string ‚ÄúEtAl‚Äù to the name</li>
  <li>if there are multiple articles from the same years and same authors, append the second article name with ‚ÄúB‚Äù, the third with ‚ÄúC‚Äù, etc.</li>
  <li>For ‚Äúto appear‚Äù articles add the string ‚ÄúToAppear‚Äù before the author last names</li>
  <li>For ‚Äúsubmitted‚Äù articles add the string ‚ÄúSubmitted‚Äù before the author last names</li>
</ul>

<p>None of the keys use underscores in order to avoid parsing issues with certain programs which would interprate them as subscripts.</p>

<p>Please keep the bib.bib file organized, otherwise mistakes/missing information is harder to find!</p>

<h2 id="add-a-publication-entry">Add a publication entry</h2>
<p>You need:</p>
<ul>
  <li>the metadata of the publication</li>
  <li>to have the following things installed locally:
    <ul>
      <li>python</li>
      <li>pyyaml (https://pyyaml.org/) (install it by running ‚Äòpip install pyyaml‚Äô in terminal)</li>
      <li>bibtexparser (https://bibtexparser.readthedocs.io/en/master/) (install it by running ‚Äòpip install bibtexparser‚Äô in terminal)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<ol>
  <li>Go to _data/bib.bib and add the new publication as a normal bibtex entry</li>
  <li>Run the bib_to_yml.py python script found in _data/ locally. You can do so by navigating to the _data folder in the terminal and typing the command ‚Äúpython bib_to_yml.py‚Äù</li>
  <li>Follow instructions under ‚Äúpublish changes‚Äù</li>
</ol>

<p>Furter Notes:</p>

<p>Step (1): If the publication is not yet published, instead of including a year, write ‚Äúto appear‚Äù (if its a manuscript that has been accepted already) or ‚Äúsubmitted‚Äù (if its a manuscript that has been submitted but not yet accepted). In the Publication section, the ‚ÄúPending‚Äù, ‚ÄúTo Appear‚Äù, and ‚ÄúSubmitted‚Äù headers will automatically appear if there is an entry in the bibtex where the year is set to ‚Äúto appear‚Äù or ‚Äúsubmitted‚Äù.</p>

<p>Step (2): We want to have a bibtex file with all the bib entries of our bibliography. However, the website only knows how to interface with yaml files, not bibtex files. So the python script takes everything in the bibtex file and converts it to a yaml file that the website can then parse. On the Publications page there is a [bibtex] button which shows the bibtex entry. This button doesn‚Äôt actually reference the bib.bib file but rather takes the information from the yaml and converts it to text which is formatted like a bibtex entry.</p>

<h2 id="change-publication-information">Change publication information</h2>
<p>Do this if you found a mistake/missing link of a publication already published to the website, or if a publication has been published and needs to be moved from the ‚Äúto appear‚Äù or ‚Äúsubmitted‚Äù sections.</p>

<h2 id="information-to-include-about-each-publication">Information to include about each publication</h2>
<p>In the bib.bib file, you‚Äôll notice that the ‚Äúheader‚Äù of each paper is tagged with either:
	1) ‚Äú@incollection {‚Ä¶}‚Äù
	2) ‚Äú@inproceedings {‚Ä¶}‚Äù
	3) ‚Äú@article {‚Ä¶}‚Äù</p>

<p>These ‚Äúheaders‚Äù mark where/how the article was published ‚Äì a chapter in a book, in the publication of conference proceedings, or in a scientific journal, respectively. While largely the same, depending on where the paper was published, different information about the article is provided in the bibtex. For each, follow this format for ordering of paper information. This helps to keep the bib.bib file organized!</p>

<p>For ‚Äú@incollection {‚Ä¶}‚Äù papers, the corresponding information should be in this order:
	- author
	- title
	- year
	- abstract
	- website
	- booktitle
	- chapter
	- editor
	- isbn
	- publisher</p>

<p>For ‚Äú@inproceedings {‚Ä¶}‚Äù papers, the corresponding information should be in this order:
	- author
	- title
	- year
	- abstract
	- website
	- journal
	- publisher
	- volume
	- issue/ number
	- pages
	- keywords
	- doi</p>

<p>For ‚Äú@article {‚Ä¶}‚Äù papers, the corresponding information should be in this order:
	- author
	- title
	-	year
	- abstract
	- website
	- book title
	- keywords
	- website</p>

<p>We want to try our best to have information in all of the fields, but it might not exist/apply or be incredibly difficult to find. Just try your best. If there is any extra information, just put it at the bottom.</p>

<h1 id="view-changes-locallytroubleshooting">View changes locally/Troubleshooting</h1>
<p>You need:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Install Jekyll locally</li>
</ul>

<ol>
  <li>Navigate to the root of the ALPS website folder using terminal and execute command ‚Äúbundle exec jekyll serve‚Äù (or ‚Äújekyll serve‚Äù)</li>
  <li>You will see an output that looks like this:
    <div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>Configuration file: /Users/stefan/Desktop/repos/ALPS_website/_config.yml
         Source: /Users/stefan/Desktop/repos/ALPS_website
    Destination: /Users/stefan/Desktop/repos/ALPS_website/_site
 Incremental build: disabled. Enable with --incremental
   Generating...
    Jekyll Feed: Generating feed for posts
                 done in 0.536 seconds.
 Auto-regeneration: enabled for '/Users/stefan/Desktop/repos/ALPS_website'
 Server address: http://127.0.0.1:4000
  Server running... press ctrl-c to stop.
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>Copy the ‚Äúserver address‚Äù and paste it as a URL in your browser. This will take you to a local version of the website. Note that this is not accessible to anyone except you, so feel free to make any changes. The changes will only become visible when you push them to the github repo.</li>
</ol>

<p>If in step (2) you do not see the above input, but an error message, this means that there was an error compiling your code. These are usually syntax errors. The messages that pop up in terminal are helpful in locating the syntax error.</p>

<p>If you make local changes with the website open locally on your browser, just hit save and the changes should automatically be reflected in your local browser. The fact that you saved the document will be reflected in the terminal in which you typed ‚Äújekyll serve‚Äù. The terminal will also show you error messages that come up as you are editing the website. Be aware that if you make a change that is fatal to the website (e.g. a syntax error), terminal will show you a red message letting you know that this error message will keep the site from working, but the locally running website will not reflect that change (or any future changes until you fix the fatal error).</p>

<p>Final word of warning: the website that you see on the webpage is already compiled and entirely the output product of the jekyll framework, meaning it does not have access to the individual .html/.md/.yml files found in this repo nor does it have any access to the liquid syntax. So none of the that code will be visible in the web browser developer tools. In order to find and fix bugs, you have to use the terminal and the repo code and can‚Äôt solely rely on the (locally running) webpage.</p>

